{"version":3,"kind":"Notebook","sha256":"eba85beac69ab48779cf316a24e5efde16151944039a9d871f838677f3de8066","slug":"dupor2023-bn-subsequent-literature","location":"/Dupor2023-bn_subsequent-literature.ipynb","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Subsequent literature (2019+)","content_includes_title":false,"kernelspec":{"name":"python3","display_name":"Python 3","language":"python"},"exports":[{"format":"ipynb","filename":"Dupor2023-bn_subsequent-literature.ipynb","url":"/Dupor2023-bn_subsequ-b8ae3988251a9a88238ecf879b319d63.ipynb"}]},"widgets":{},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Since 2019, the literature most related to ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"D0k06HYiy8"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"Dupor2023-bn","identifier":"dupor2023-bn","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Dupor ","key":"ngARHSFxt1"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"d9fpEJTxul"}],"key":"WwONtzNlQN"},{"type":"text","value":" (2023)","key":"tsqbQYb65A"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"q648dlsEak"}],"key":"mErENRIzEr"},{"type":"text","value":" has moved from asking whether fiscal multipliers are positive to asking which multiplier we mean, in which environment, and through which distributional channels it operates. A first direction is sharper theory of heterogeneous-agent transmission under realistic policy regimes. ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"YlsbxQK1ug"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"fiscal_hagedorn_2019","identifier":"fiscal_hagedorn_2019","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Hagedorn ","key":"Zb0sUYfmSx"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"mHloXHs3Mu"}],"key":"bk3cmCJrlY"},{"type":"text","value":" (2019)","key":"E4Bunxrzay"}],"enumerator":"2","key":"lQux4zcHOD"}],"key":"OGqifNNaNY"},{"type":"text","value":" formalizes a HANK environment with incomplete markets, nominal rigidities, and endogenous labor-market responses, showing that financing and monetary accommodation are first-order determinants of multiplier size. This work helped normalize the idea that a single “fiscal multiplier” is not a structural constant: it varies with deficits versus contemporaneous taxation, the policy rule followed by the central bank, and the distribution of marginal propensities to consume across households. That line is extended and systematized by ","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"XKXvGgcroB"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"fiscal_auclert_2024","identifier":"fiscal_auclert_2024","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Auclert ","key":"hjladJ00zc"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"BZLhVpFIb0"}],"key":"Dod6aLVWpb"},{"type":"text","value":" (2024)","key":"XgdnT365pf"}],"enumerator":"3","key":"J57hBt92nR"}],"key":"AcMlGUolQq"},{"type":"text","value":", which provides a unified modern framework for fiscal and monetary interactions in heterogeneous-agent models. The cutting-edge shift here is methodological as much as substantive: policy analysis is increasingly done in models disciplined by distributional moments and realistic household balance sheets rather than representative-agent shortcuts.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"xvXb0aV2ot"}],"key":"I071ywy4Oz"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A second direction is stronger emphasis on state dependence and nonlinearities. While post-crisis work had already suggested larger multipliers near the effective lower bound, newer papers investigate richer nonlinear mechanisms and sign asymmetries. ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"x5tmuVvDE9"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"nonlinear_brinca_2019","identifier":"nonlinear_brinca_2019","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Brinca ","key":"mkj7w0s5MI"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"n4rBA8OX0W"}],"key":"yEGTQkAq36"},{"type":"text","value":" (2019)","key":"Lwsy6m4qOQ"}],"enumerator":"4","key":"p6y46OyMNJ"}],"key":"thz9mxHMWL"},{"type":"text","value":" and ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"SyT7rnqn9E"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"understanding_barnichon_2021","identifier":"understanding_barnichon_2021","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Barnichon ","key":"LgB3YmKsJw"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"Gh7Avvme4l"}],"key":"MdMCUoTaG4"},{"type":"text","value":" (2021)","key":"LdSjHwEClu"}],"enumerator":"5","key":"VScwNusMnE"}],"key":"GUlaotcPS1"},{"type":"text","value":" push this agenda by showing that the effects of fiscal expansions and contractions need not be symmetric and may depend on labor-market slack, financing conditions, and the composition of shocks. In parallel, ","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"p5gLP4tJ9c"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"heterogeneous_bernardini_2020","identifier":"heterogeneous_bernardini_2020","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Bernardini ","key":"S4EbTK2C1m"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"wL3xyblnXL"}],"key":"ZV7wQ8bkPG"},{"type":"text","value":" (2020)","key":"xwCswnZOjP"}],"enumerator":"6","key":"um6c1V9Cwn"}],"key":"p7Hvnf0Dxk"},{"type":"text","value":" documents substantial variation in multiplier estimates around the Great Recession period, reinforcing the view that “average” multipliers can hide large cyclical and cross-country heterogeneity. Together, these papers moved the field away from point estimates toward conditional policy rules: when policymakers ask for a multiplier, the modern answer is “conditional on regime, sign, and composition.”","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"Y8KBfwf0w8"}],"key":"eKYhy7wV3h"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"A third direction, very close to the Dupor et al. research design, is local-to-aggregate mapping in spatial economies. Earlier regional IV designs established credible local treatment effects; the frontier is now to recover general-equilibrium propagation through production and trade linkages. ","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"mPKo81o1De"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"spatial_casas_2025","identifier":"spatial_casas_2025","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Casas ","key":"TVj1YNbYTB"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"QnE67EeVfj"}],"key":"jN9sVjd0G0"},{"type":"text","value":" (2025)","key":"Fr4wVylNvD"}],"enumerator":"7","key":"XE7ItvgLzi"}],"key":"TNKcrzMjlL"},{"type":"text","value":" illustrates this trajectory with a spatial general-equilibrium treatment of local spending multipliers in EU regions, where cross-region demand and supply linkages are central rather than residual. This is conceptually aligned with the multi-region structure in ","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"Zn0aSygzKr"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"Dupor2023-bn","identifier":"dupor2023-bn","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Dupor ","key":"YXz07QfcYe"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"ju6Ueqwgjy"}],"key":"Vlw4NOFk1x"},{"type":"text","value":" (2023)","key":"XgCg1m7ztf"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"TJioBvqnEc"}],"key":"dYKsArQEHJ"},{"type":"text","value":": local spending shocks generate spillovers that can make aggregate effects exceed local direct effects. The practical implication is that new empirical work increasingly combines regional quasi-experiments with explicit network or spatial structure, instead of treating spillovers as a nuisance. In the same spirit, ","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"sXPKs9mUpG"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"fiscal_sheremirov_2022","identifier":"fiscal_sheremirov_2022","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Sheremirov & Spirovska (2022)","key":"pziNAtGqaF"}],"enumerator":"8","key":"y8WK1Dfadz"}],"key":"hgCsIC81Z0"},{"type":"text","value":" broadens external validity by comparing advanced and developing economies using military-spending variation, highlighting that institutions and macro regimes materially alter transmission.","position":{"start":{"line":7,"column":1},"end":{"line":7,"column":1}},"key":"jDGFK480Bn"}],"key":"lfud2VA3th"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Related but distinct, another emerging branch studies household balance-sheet channels beyond standard transfer episodes. ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"v4YCuyrHEz"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"macroeconomic_auclert_2019","identifier":"macroeconomic_auclert_2019","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Auclert ","key":"NXhA3hoy0D"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"JIC4F7rod7"}],"key":"kgSOsZGTQ3"},{"type":"text","value":" (2019)","key":"s2rqm19GtY"}],"enumerator":"9","key":"lgO2UvEUkF"}],"key":"gUUtDGAYaR"},{"type":"text","value":" (debt relief and bankruptcy protections) and ","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"swdd7xtPXA"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"stock_chodorowreich_2021","identifier":"stock_chodorowreich_2021","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Chodorow-reich ","key":"OT1Qc19LO4"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"wVRoEDOfRv"}],"key":"ZrR8dIPVe5"},{"type":"text","value":" (2021)","key":"aVB6t8sOlX"}],"enumerator":"10","key":"hZfnQZDIUJ"}],"key":"v9wpIYqryj"},{"type":"text","value":" (stock-market wealth and local labor markets) reinforce a broader post-2019 conclusion: fiscal and quasi-fiscal policies work through heterogeneous exposures to income, debt, and asset-price changes. This complements the consumption-MPC logic behind Dupor et al. and points to a richer notion of stimulus design where targeting depends not only on current income but also on liquidity, leverage, and wealth composition.","position":{"start":{"line":9,"column":1},"end":{"line":9,"column":1}},"key":"FqiqPc0zEv"}],"key":"EOOtpHcgsT"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Putting these strands together, the main research directions that emerged after 2019 are: (i) integrating fiscal and monetary policy in tractable HANK frameworks suitable for quantitative policy experiments; (ii) estimating regime-dependent, nonlinear multipliers rather than unconditional averages; (iii) connecting local causal estimates to national outcomes through explicit spatial and network propagation; and (iv) embedding household balance-sheet heterogeneity directly into fiscal design questions. The cutting edge now is not a single new estimate, but a synthesis: micro-founded heterogeneity plus credible quasi-experimental variation plus explicit aggregation structure. Under this view, the core contribution of ","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"RwGPuEucK9"},{"type":"citeGroup","kind":"narrative","children":[{"type":"cite","kind":"narrative","label":"Dupor2023-bn","identifier":"dupor2023-bn","children":[{"type":"text","value":"Dupor ","key":"ai6lxopFJq"},{"type":"emphasis","children":[{"type":"text","value":"et al.","key":"lVQdWS7koZ"}],"key":"l2gtdZnxnp"},{"type":"text","value":" (2023)","key":"WKLLVmSQPe"}],"enumerator":"1","key":"xcZGUfeBRK"}],"key":"XCe86PGz0Z"},{"type":"text","value":" looks increasingly prescient, because it anticipated exactly this workflow by combining regional consumption evidence with a multi-region heterogeneous-agent model.","position":{"start":{"line":11,"column":1},"end":{"line":11,"column":1}},"key":"wRjjmEJ6D9"}],"key":"tCDwdghmZb"}],"key":"NJDCejYr0u"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Most important papers for where the field is heading (3-5)","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"kNnsIl0GzK"}],"identifier":"most-important-papers-for-where-the-field-is-heading-3-5","label":"Most important papers for where the field is heading (3-5)","html_id":"most-important-papers-for-where-the-field-is-heading-3-5","implicit":true,"key":"qywAgT52Xj"},{"type":"list","ordered":true,"start":1,"spread":false,"position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":4,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"strong","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":